        <td width="100%" valign="top"><div align="center">
          <p class="hppghdr"><img src="../../imglib/new/UnifiedTransProg.jpg" width="640" height="100"></p>
          <p align="left">The <a href="../utp/utp.htm"> Unified Transportation Program</a> is TxDOT&rsquo;s ten-year plan for developing and constructing transportation projects in your area and the rest of the state. It is a planning and programming tool that coordinates desired local and regional transportation projects with statewide transportation goals and priorities. The UTP also allows for the systematic distribution of limited transportation funds within the state. It is developed and updated annually through a collaborative process between officials representing your area and state agencies, primarily TxDOT, and approved by the Texas Transportation Commission (TTC). </p>
          <p align="left">The UTP is divided into two parts: the <a href="ftp://ftp.dot.state.tx.us/pub/txdot-info/tpp/2004smp.pdf"> Statewide Mobility Program</a> (SMP) and the <a href="ftp://ftp.dot.state.tx.us/pub/txdot-info/tpp/final2005spp.pdf"> Statewide Preservation Program</a> (SPP). There are 12 categories of funding within the two parts, 9 in the SMP and 3 in the SPP. </p>
          <p align="left">The Metropolitan Planning Organization of your city or region creates, approves, and publishes a short-range Transportation Improvement Program (TIP) for your area. The TIP represents the next 3 to 5 years and is part of Larger metropolitan regions in the state create a the Metropolitan Transportation Plan (MTP ) which covers your region&rsquo;s needs for the next 20 years . ). TIPs from all cities and regions within the state are combined in to make up the <a href="http://www.dot.state.tx.us/tpp/stip/"> Statewide Transportation Improvement Program (STIP)</a>. </p>
          <p align="left">Title 23 of the United States Code includes the following statewide transportation improvement program (STIP) requirements paraphrased below for clarity: </p>
          <blockquote><p align="left">A STIP shall include projects within the boundaries of the state that are proposed for funding under Title 23 and the Federal Transit Act. Projects will be consistent with the state long-range plan and the metropolitan planning organization Transportation Improvement Programs (TIPs). In non-attainment areas (areas that do not conform to air quality standards) projects will conform to the applicable State Implementation Plan developed pursuant to the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1991. The STIP shall include projects, or phases of projects, only if full funding can reasonably be anticipated to be available for the project within the time period contemplated for completion of the project. The STIP shall also reflect the priorities for programming and expenditures of funds, including transportation enhancements.</p></blockquote>
		  <p align="left"> For more on the STIP, including the 2004-2006 version, click <a href="http://www.dot.state.tx.us/tpp/stip/">here</a>. </p>
          <p align="left" class="hppghdr">&nbsp;</p>
